117  public uint bytesread; /* [w] Fill this in before setting result code to tell FMOD how many bytes were read. */
118  public RESULT result; /* [r/w] Result code, FMOD_OK tells the system it is ready to consume the data. Set this last! Default value = FMOD_ERR_NOTREADY. */
119 
120  public IntPtr userdata; /* [r] User data pointer. */

241  /*
242  [ENUM]
243  [
244  [DESCRIPTION]
245  These output types are used with System::setOutput/System::getOutput, to choose which output method to use.
246 
247  [REMARKS]
248  To drive the output synchronously, and to disable FMOD's timing thread, use the FMOD_INIT_NONREALTIME flag.
249 
250  To pass information to the driver when initializing fmod use the extradriverdata parameter for the following reasons.
251  <li>FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_WAVWRITER - extradriverdata is a pointer to a char * filename that the wav writer will output to.
252  <li>FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_WAVWRITER_NRT - extradriverdata is a pointer to a char * filename that the wav writer will output to.
253  <li>FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_DSOUND - extradriverdata is a pointer to a HWND so that FMOD can set the focus on the audio for a particular window.
254  <li>FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_GC - extradriverdata is a pointer to a FMOD_ARAMBLOCK_INFO struct. This can be found in fmodgc.h.
255  Currently these are the only FMOD drivers that take extra information. Other unknown plugins may have different requirements.
256 
257  [PLATFORMS]
258  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
259 
260  [SEE_ALSO]
261  System::setOutput
262  System::getOutput
263  System::setSoftwareFormat
264  System::getSoftwareFormat
265  System::init
266  ]
267  */
268  public enum OUTPUTTYPE :int
269  {
270  AUTODETECT, /* Picks the best output mode for the platform. This is the default. */
271 
272  UNKNOWN, /* All - 3rd party plugin, unknown. This is for use with System::getOutput only. */
273  NOSOUND, /* All - All calls in this mode succeed but make no sound. */
274  WAVWRITER, /* All - Writes output to fmodoutput.wav by default. Use the 'extradriverdata' parameter in System::init, by simply passing the filename as a string, to set the wav filename. */
275  NOSOUND_NRT, /* All - Non-realtime version of _NOSOUND. User can drive mixer with System::update at whatever rate they want. */
276  WAVWRITER_NRT, /* All - Non-realtime version of _WAVWRITER. User can drive mixer with System::update at whatever rate they want. */
277 
278  DSOUND, /* Win32/Win64 - DirectSound output. (Default on Windows XP and below) */
279  WINMM, /* Win32/Win64 - Windows Multimedia output. */
280  WASAPI, /* Win32 - Windows Audio Session API. (Default on Windows Vista and above) */
281  ASIO, /* Win32 - Low latency ASIO 2.0 driver. */
282  OSS, /* Linux/Linux64 - Open Sound System output. (Default on Linux, third preference) */
283  ALSA, /* Linux/Linux64 - Advanced Linux Sound Architecture output. (Default on Linux, second preference if available) */
284  ESD, /* Linux/Linux64 - Enlightment Sound Daemon output. */
285  PULSEAUDIO, /* Linux/Linux64 - PulseAudio output. (Default on Linux, first preference if available) */
286  COREAUDIO, /* Mac - Macintosh CoreAudio output. (Default on Mac) */
287  XBOX360, /* Xbox 360 - Native Xbox360 output. (Default on Xbox 360) */
288  PSP, /* PSP - Native PSP output. (Default on PSP) */
289  PS3, /* PS3 - Native PS3 output. (Default on PS3) */
290  NGP, /* NGP - Native NGP output. (Default on NGP) */
291  WII, /* Wii - Native Wii output. (Default on Wii) */
292  _3DS, /* 3DS - Native 3DS output (Default on 3DS) */
293  AUDIOTRACK, /* Android - Java Audio Track output. (Default on Android 2.2 and below) */
294  OPENSL, /* Android - OpenSL ES output. (Default on Android 2.3 and above) */
295 
296  MAX /* Maximum number of output types supported. */
297  }

403 
404  /*
405  [ENUM]
406  [
407  [DESCRIPTION]
408  These are speaker types defined for use with the System::setSpeakerMode or System::getSpeakerMode command.
409 
410  [REMARKS]
411  These are important notes on speaker modes in regards to sounds created with FMOD_SOFTWARE.<br>
412  Note below the phrase 'sound channels' is used. These are the subchannels inside a sound, they are not related and
413  have nothing to do with the FMOD class "Channel".<br>
414  For example a mono sound has 1 sound channel, a stereo sound has 2 sound channels, and an AC3 or 6 channel wav file have 6 "sound channels".<br>
415  <br>
416  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_RAW<br>
417  ---------------------<br>
418  This mode is for output devices that are not specifically mono/stereo/quad/surround/5.1 or 7.1, but are multichannel.<br>
419  Sound channels map to speakers sequentially, so a mono sound maps to output speaker 0, stereo sound maps to output speaker 0 & 1.<br>
420  The user assumes knowledge of the speaker order. FMOD_SPEAKER enumerations may not apply, so raw channel indicies should be used.<br>
421  Multichannel sounds map input channels to output channels 1:1. <br>
422  Channel::setPan and Channel::setSpeakerMix do not work.<br>
423  Speaker levels must be manually set with Channel::setSpeakerLevels.<br>
424  <br>
425  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_MONO<br>
426  ---------------------<br>
427  This mode is for a 1 speaker arrangement.<br>
428  Panning does not work in this speaker mode.<br>
429  Mono, stereo and multichannel sounds have each sound channel played on the one speaker unity.<br>
430  Mix behaviour for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setSpeakerLevels.<br>
431  Channel::setSpeakerMix does not work.<br>
432  <br>
433  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_STEREO<br>
434  -----------------------<br>
435  This mode is for 2 speaker arrangements that have a left and right speaker.<br>
436  <li>Mono sounds default to an even distribution between left and right. They can be panned with Channel::setPan.<br>
437  <li>Stereo sounds default to the middle, or full left in the left speaker and full right in the right speaker.
438  <li>They can be cross faded with Channel::setPan.<br>
439  <li>Multichannel sounds have each sound channel played on each speaker at unity.<br>
440  <li>Mix behaviour for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setSpeakerLevels.<br>
441  <li>Channel::setSpeakerMix works but only front left and right parameters are used, the rest are ignored.<br>
442  <br>
443  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_QUAD<br>
444  ------------------------<br>
445  This mode is for 4 speaker arrangements that have a front left, front right, rear left and a rear right speaker.<br>
446  <li>Mono sounds default to an even distribution between front left and front right. They can be panned with Channel::setPan.<br>
447  <li>Stereo sounds default to the left sound channel played on the front left, and the right sound channel played on the front right.<br>
448  <li>They can be cross faded with Channel::setPan.<br>
449  <li>Multichannel sounds default to all of their sound channels being played on each speaker in order of input.<br>
450  <li>Mix behaviour for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setSpeakerLevels.<br>
451  <li>Channel::setSpeakerMix works but side left, side right, center and lfe are ignored.<br>
452  <br>
453  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_SURROUND<br>
454  ------------------------<br>
455  This mode is for 4 speaker arrangements that have a front left, front right, front center and a rear center.<br>
456  <li>Mono sounds default to the center speaker. They can be panned with Channel::setPan.<br>
457  <li>Stereo sounds default to the left sound channel played on the front left, and the right sound channel played on the front right.
458  <li>They can be cross faded with Channel::setPan.<br>
459  <li>Multichannel sounds default to all of their sound channels being played on each speaker in order of input.<br>
460  <li>Mix behaviour for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setSpeakerLevels.<br>
461  <li>Channel::setSpeakerMix works but side left, side right and lfe are ignored, and rear left / rear right are averaged into the rear speaker.<br>
462  <br>
463  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_5POINT1<br>
464  ------------------------<br>
465  This mode is for 5.1 speaker arrangements that have a left/right/center/rear left/rear right and a subwoofer speaker.<br>
466  <li>Mono sounds default to the center speaker. They can be panned with Channel::setPan.<br>
467  <li>Stereo sounds default to the left sound channel played on the front left, and the right sound channel played on the front right.
468  <li>They can be cross faded with Channel::setPan.<br>
469  <li>Multichannel sounds default to all of their sound channels being played on each speaker in order of input.
470  <li>Mix behaviour for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setSpeakerLevels.<br>
471  <li>Channel::setSpeakerMix works but side left / side right are ignored.<br>
472  <br>
473  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_7POINT1<br>
474  ------------------------<br>
475  This mode is for 7.1 speaker arrangements that have a left/right/center/rear left/rear right/side left/side right
476  and a subwoofer speaker.<br>
477  <li>Mono sounds default to the center speaker. They can be panned with Channel::setPan.<br>
478  <li>Stereo sounds default to the left sound channel played on the front left, and the right sound channel played on the front right.
479  <li>They can be cross faded with Channel::setPan.<br>
480  <li>Multichannel sounds default to all of their sound channels being played on each speaker in order of input.
481  <li>Mix behaviour for multichannel sounds can be set with Channel::setSpeakerLevels.<br>
482  <li>Channel::setSpeakerMix works and every parameter is used to set the balance of a sound in any speaker.<br>
483  <br>
484  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_PROLOGIC<br>
485  ------------------------------------------------------<br>
486  This mode is for mono, stereo, 5.1 and 7.1 speaker arrangements, as it is backwards and forwards compatible with stereo,
487  but to get a surround effect a Dolby Prologic or Prologic 2 hardware decoder / amplifier is needed.<br>
488  Pan behaviour is the same as FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_5POINT1.<br>
489  <br>
490  If this function is called the numoutputchannels setting in System::setSoftwareFormat is overwritten.<br>
491  <br>
492  For 3D sounds, panning is determined at runtime by the 3D subsystem based on the speaker mode to determine which speaker the
493  sound should be placed in.<br>
494 
495  FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_MYEARS<br>
496  ------------------------------------------------------<br>
497  This mode is for headphones. This will attempt to load a MyEars profile (see myears.net.au) and use it to generate
498  surround sound on headphones using a personalized HRTF algorithm, for realistic 3d sound.<br>
499  Pan behavior is the same as FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_7POINT1.<br>
500  MyEars speaker mode will automatically be set if the speakermode is FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_STEREO and the MyEars profile exists.<br>
501  If this mode is set explicitly, FMOD_INIT_DISABLE_MYEARS_AUTODETECT has no effect.<br>
502  If this mode is set explicitly and the MyEars profile does not exist, FMOD_ERR_OUTPUT_DRIVERCALL will be returned.
503 
504  [PLATFORMS]
505  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
506 
507  [SEE_ALSO]
508  System::setSpeakerMode
509  System::getSpeakerMode
510  System::getDriverCaps
511  Channel::setSpeakerLevels
512  ]
513  */
514  public enum SPEAKERMODE :int
515  {
516  RAW, /* There is no specific speakermode. Sound channels are mapped in order of input to output. See remarks for more information. */
517  MONO, /* The speakers are monaural. */
518  STEREO, /* The speakers are stereo (DEFAULT). */
519  QUAD, /* 4 speaker setup. This includes front left, front right, rear left, rear right. */
520  SURROUND, /* 4 speaker setup. This includes front left, front right, center, rear center (rear left/rear right are averaged). */
521  _5POINT1, /* 5.1 speaker setup. This includes front left, front right, center, rear left, rear right and a subwoofer. */
522  _7POINT1, /* 7.1 speaker setup. This includes front left, front right, center, rear left, rear right, side left, side right and a subwoofer. */
523 
524  PROLOGIC, /* Stereo output, but data is encoded in a way that is picked up by a Prologic/Prologic2 decoder and split into a 5.1 speaker setup. */
525  MYEARS, /* Stereo output, but data is encoded using personalized HRTF algorithms. See myears.net.au */
526 
527  MAX, /* Maximum number of speaker modes supported. */
528  }
529

531  /*
532  [ENUM]
533  [
534  [DESCRIPTION]
535  These are speaker types defined for use with the Channel::setSpeakerLevels command.
536  It can also be used for speaker placement in the System::setSpeakerPosition command.
537 
538  [REMARKS]
539  If you are using FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_RAW and speaker assignments are meaningless, just cast a raw integer value to this type.<br>
540  For example (FMOD_SPEAKER)7 would use the 7th speaker (also the same as FMOD_SPEAKER_SIDE_RIGHT).<br>
541  Values higher than this can be used if an output system has more than 8 speaker types / output channels. 15 is the current maximum.
542 
543  [PLATFORMS]
544  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
545

559  LOW_FREQUENCY,
560  BACK_LEFT,
561  BACK_RIGHT,
562  SIDE_LEFT,
563  SIDE_RIGHT,
564 
565  MAX, /* Maximum number of speaker types supported. */
566  MONO = FRONT_LEFT, /* For use with FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_MONO and Channel::SetSpeakerLevels. Mapped to same value as FMOD_SPEAKER_FRONT_LEFT. */
567  NULL = MAX, /* A non speaker. Use this to send. */
568  SBL = SIDE_LEFT, /* For use with FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_7POINT1 on PS3 where the extra speakers are surround back inside of side speakers. */
569  SBR = SIDE_RIGHT, /* For use with FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_7POINT1 on PS3 where the extra speakers are surround back inside of side speakers. */

603  Initialization flags. Use them with System::init in the flags parameter to change various behaviour.
604

606 
607  [PLATFORMS]

609 
610  [SEE_ALSO]
611  System::init
612  ]
613  */
614  public enum INITFLAGS :int
615  {
616  NORMAL = 0x00000000, /* All platforms - Initialize normally */
617  STREAM_FROM_UPDATE = 0x00000001, /* All platforms - No stream thread is created internally. Streams are driven from System::update. Mainly used with non-realtime outputs. */
618  _3D_RIGHTHANDED = 0x00000002, /* All platforms - FMOD will treat +X as left, +Y as up and +Z as forwards. */
619  SOFTWARE_DISABLE = 0x00000004, /* All platforms - Disable software mixer to save memory. Anything created with FMOD_SOFTWARE will fail and DSP will not work. */
620  OCCLUSION_LOWPASS = 0x00000008, /* All platforms - All FMOD_SOFTWARE (and FMOD_HARDWARE on 3DS and NGP) with FMOD_3D based voices will add a software lowpass filter effect into the DSP chain which is automatically used when Channel::set3DOcclusion is used or the geometry API. */
621  HRTF_LOWPASS = 0x00000010, /* All platforms - All FMOD_SOFTWARE (and FMOD_HARDWARE on 3DS and NGP) with FMOD_3D based voices will add a software lowpass filter effect into the DSP chain which causes sounds to sound duller when the sound goes behind the listener. Use System::setAdvancedSettings to adjust cutoff frequency. */
622  SOFTWARE_REVERB_LOWMEM = 0x00000040, /* All platforms - SFX reverb is run using 22/24khz delay buffers, halving the memory required. */
623  ENABLE_PROFILE = 0x00000020, /* All platforms - Enable TCP/IP based host which allows "DSPNet Listener.exe" to connect to it, and view the DSP dataflow network graph in real-time. */
624  VOL0_BECOMES_VIRTUAL = 0x00000080, /* All platforms - Any sounds that are 0 volume will go virtual and not be processed except for having their positions updated virtually. Use System::setAdvancedSettings to adjust what volume besides zero to switch to virtual at. */
625  WASAPI_EXCLUSIVE = 0x00000100, /* Win32 Vista only - for WASAPI output - Enable exclusive access to hardware, lower latency at the expense of excluding other applications from accessing the audio hardware. */
626  DISABLEDOLBY = 0x00100000, /* Wii / 3DS - Disable Dolby Pro Logic surround. Speakermode will be set to STEREO even if user has selected surround in the system settings. */
627  WII_DISABLEDOLBY = 0x00100000, /* Wii only - Disable Dolby Pro Logic surround. Speakermode will be set to STEREO even if user has selected surround in the Wii system settings. */
628  _360_MUSICMUTENOTPAUSE = 0x00200000, /* Xbox 360 only - The "music" channelgroup which by default pauses when custom 360 dashboard music is played, can be changed to mute (therefore continues playing) instead of pausing, by using this flag. */
629  SYNCMIXERWITHUPDATE = 0x00400000, /* Win32/Wii/PS3/Xbox 360 - FMOD Mixer thread is woken up to do a mix when System::update is called rather than waking periodically on its own timer. */
630  DTS_NEURALSURROUND = 0x02000000, /* Win32/Mac/Linux - Use DTS Neural surround downmixing from 7.1 if speakermode set to FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_STEREO or FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_5POINT1. Internal DSP structure will be set to 7.1. */
631  GEOMETRY_USECLOSEST = 0x04000000, /* All platforms - With the geometry engine, only process the closest polygon rather than accumulating all polygons the sound to listener line intersects. */
632  DISABLE_MYEARS_AUTODETECT = 0x08000000 /* Win32 - Disables automatic setting of FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_STEREO to FMOD_SPEAKERMODE_MYEARS if the MyEars profile exists on the PC. MyEars is HRTF 7.1 downmixing through headphones. */
633  }

720  /*
721  [DEFINE]
722  [
723  [NAME]
724  FMOD_MODE
725 
726  [DESCRIPTION]
727  Sound description bitfields, bitwise OR them together for loading and describing sounds.
728 
729  [REMARKS]
730  By default a sound will open as a static sound that is decompressed fully into memory.<br>
731  To have a sound stream instead, use FMOD_CREATESTREAM.<br>
732  Some opening modes (ie FMOD_OPENUSER, FMOD_OPENMEMORY, FMOD_OPENRAW) will need extra information.<br>
733  This can be provided using the FMOD_CREATESOUNDEXINFO structure.
734 
735  [PLATFORMS]
736  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
737 
738  [SEE_ALSO]
739  System::createSound
740  System::createStream
741  Sound::setMode
742  Sound::getMode
743  Channel::setMode
744  Channel::getMode
745  Sound::set3DCustomRolloff
746  Channel::set3DCustomRolloff
747  ]
748  */
749  public enum MODE :uint
750  {
751  DEFAULT = 0x00000000, /* FMOD_DEFAULT is a default sound type. Equivalent to all the defaults listed below. FMOD_LOOP_OFF, FMOD_2D, FMOD_HARDWARE. */
752  LOOP_OFF = 0x00000001, /* For non looping sounds. (default). Overrides FMOD_LOOP_NORMAL / FMOD_LOOP_BIDI. */
753  LOOP_NORMAL = 0x00000002, /* For forward looping sounds. */
754  LOOP_BIDI = 0x00000004, /* For bidirectional looping sounds. (only works on software mixed static sounds). */
755  _2D = 0x00000008, /* Ignores any 3d processing. (default). */
756  _3D = 0x00000010, /* Makes the sound positionable in 3D. Overrides FMOD_2D. */
757  HARDWARE = 0x00000020, /* Attempts to make sounds use hardware acceleration. (default). */
758  SOFTWARE = 0x00000040, /* Makes sound reside in software. Overrides FMOD_HARDWARE. Use this for FFT, DSP, 2D multi speaker support and other software related features. */
759  CREATESTREAM = 0x00000080, /* Decompress at runtime, streaming from the source provided (standard stream). Overrides FMOD_CREATESAMPLE. */
760  CREATESAMPLE = 0x00000100, /* Decompress at loadtime, decompressing or decoding whole file into memory as the target sample format. (standard sample). */
761  CREATECOMPRESSEDSAMPLE = 0x00000200, /* Load MP2, MP3, IMAADPCM or XMA into memory and leave it compressed. During playback the FMOD software mixer will decode it in realtime as a 'compressed sample'. Can only be used in combination with FMOD_SOFTWARE. */
762  OPENUSER = 0x00000400, /* Opens a user created static sample or stream. Use FMOD_CREATESOUNDEXINFO to specify format and/or read callbacks. If a user created 'sample' is created with no read callback, the sample will be empty. Use FMOD_Sound_Lock and FMOD_Sound_Unlock to place sound data into the sound if this is the case. */
763  OPENMEMORY = 0x00000800, /* "name_or_data" will be interpreted as a pointer to memory instead of filename for creating sounds. */
764  OPENMEMORY_POINT = 0x10000000, /* "name_or_data" will be interpreted as a pointer to memory instead of filename for creating sounds. Use FMOD_CREATESOUNDEXINFO to specify length. This differs to FMOD_OPENMEMORY in that it uses the memory as is, without duplicating the memory into its own buffers. FMOD_SOFTWARE only. Doesn't work with FMOD_HARDWARE, as sound hardware cannot access main ram on a lot of platforms. Cannot be freed after open, only after Sound::release. Will not work if the data is compressed and FMOD_CREATECOMPRESSEDSAMPLE is not used. */
765  OPENRAW = 0x00001000, /* Will ignore file format and treat as raw pcm. User may need to declare if data is FMOD_SIGNED or FMOD_UNSIGNED */
766  OPENONLY = 0x00002000, /* Just open the file, dont prebuffer or read. Good for fast opens for info, or when sound::readData is to be used. */
767  ACCURATETIME = 0x00004000, /* For FMOD_CreateSound - for accurate FMOD_Sound_GetLength / FMOD_Channel_SetPosition on VBR MP3, AAC and MOD/S3M/XM/IT/MIDI files. Scans file first, so takes longer to open. FMOD_OPENONLY does not affect this. */
768  MPEGSEARCH = 0x00008000, /* For corrupted / bad MP3 files. This will search all the way through the file until it hits a valid MPEG header. Normally only searches for 4k. */
769  NONBLOCKING = 0x00010000, /* For opening sounds and getting streamed subsounds (seeking) asyncronously. Use Sound::getOpenState to poll the state of the sound as it opens or retrieves the subsound in the background. */
770  UNIQUE = 0x00020000, /* Unique sound, can only be played one at a time */
771  _3D_HEADRELATIVE = 0x00040000, /* Make the sound's position, velocity and orientation relative to the listener. */
772  _3D_WORLDRELATIVE = 0x00080000, /* Make the sound's position, velocity and orientation absolute (relative to the world). (DEFAULT) */
773  _3D_INVERSEROLLOFF = 0x00100000, /* This sound will follow the inverse rolloff model where mindistance = full volume, maxdistance = where sound stops attenuating, and rolloff is fixed according to the global rolloff factor. (DEFAULT) */
774  _3D_LINEARSQUAREROLLOFF= 0x00400000, /* This sound will follow a linear-square rolloff model where mindistance = full volume, maxdistance = silence. Rolloffscale is ignored. */
775  _3D_LOGROLLOFF = 0x00100000, /* This sound will follow the standard logarithmic rolloff model where mindistance = full volume, maxdistance = where sound stops attenuating, and rolloff is fixed according to the global rolloff factor. (default) */
776  _3D_LINEARROLLOFF = 0x00200000, /* This sound will follow a linear rolloff model where mindistance = full volume, maxdistance = silence. */
777  _3D_CUSTOMROLLOFF = 0x04000000, /* This sound will follow a rolloff model defined by Sound::set3DCustomRolloff / Channel::set3DCustomRolloff. */
778  _3D_IGNOREGEOMETRY = 0x40000000, /* Is not affect by geometry occlusion. If not specified in Sound::setMode, or Channel::setMode, the flag is cleared and it is affected by geometry again. */
779  CDDA_FORCEASPI = 0x00400000, /* For CDDA sounds only - use ASPI instead of NTSCSI to access the specified CD/DVD device. */
780  CDDA_JITTERCORRECT = 0x00800000, /* For CDDA sounds only - perform jitter correction. Jitter correction helps produce a more accurate CDDA stream at the cost of more CPU time. */
781  UNICODE = 0x01000000, /* Filename is double-byte unicode. */
782  IGNORETAGS = 0x02000000, /* Skips id3v2/asf/etc tag checks when opening a sound, to reduce seek/read overhead when opening files (helps with CD performance). */
783  LOWMEM = 0x08000000, /* Removes some features from samples to give a lower memory overhead, like Sound::getName. */
784  LOADSECONDARYRAM = 0x20000000, /* Load sound into the secondary RAM of supported platform. On PS3, sounds will be loaded into RSX/VRAM. */
785  VIRTUAL_PLAYFROMSTART = 0x80000000 /* For sounds that start virtual (due to being quiet or low importance), instead of swapping back to audible, and playing at the correct offset according to time, this flag makes the sound play from the start. */
786  }

819  [ENUM]

821  [DESCRIPTION]

823  are played than are specified with SoundGroup::setMaxAudible.
824 
825  [REMARKS]
826  When using FMOD_SOUNDGROUP_BEHAVIOR_MUTE, SoundGroup::setMuteFadeSpeed can be used to stop a sudden transition.
827  Instead, the time specified will be used to cross fade between the sounds that go silent and the ones that become audible.
828 
829  [PLATFORMS]
830  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii

836  SoundGroup::getMaxAudible
837  SoundGroup::setMuteFadeSpeed
838  SoundGroup::getMuteFadeSpeed
839  ]

841  public enum SOUNDGROUP_BEHAVIOR :int
842  {
843  BEHAVIOR_FAIL, /* Any sound played that puts the sound count over the SoundGroup::setMaxAudible setting, will simply fail during System::playSound. */
844  BEHAVIOR_MUTE, /* Any sound played that puts the sound count over the SoundGroup::setMaxAudible setting, will be silent, then if another sound in the group stops the sound that was silent before becomes audible again. */
845  BEHAVIOR_STEALLOWEST /* Any sound played that puts the sound count over the SoundGroup::setMaxAudible setting, will steal the quietest / least important sound playing in the group. */
846  }

930  /*
931  [ENUM]
932  [
933  [DESCRIPTION]
934  List of windowing methods used in spectrum analysis to reduce leakage / transient signals intefering with the analysis.
935  This is a problem with analysis of continuous signals that only have a small portion of the signal sample (the fft window size).
936  Windowing the signal with a curve or triangle tapers the sides of the fft window to help alleviate this problem.
937 
938  [REMARKS]
939  Cyclic signals such as a sine wave that repeat their cycle in a multiple of the window size do not need windowing.
940  I.e. If the sine wave repeats every 1024, 512, 256 etc samples and the FMOD fft window is 1024, then the signal would not need windowing.
941  Not windowing is the same as FMOD_DSP_FFT_WINDOW_RECT, which is the default.
942  If the cycle of the signal (ie the sine wave) is not a multiple of the window size, it will cause frequency abnormalities, so a different windowing method is needed.
943  <exclude>
944 
945  FMOD_DSP_FFT_WINDOW_RECT.
946  <img src = "rectangle.gif"></img>
947 
948  FMOD_DSP_FFT_WINDOW_TRIANGLE.
949  <img src = "triangle.gif"></img>
950 
951  FMOD_DSP_FFT_WINDOW_HAMMING.
952  <img src = "hamming.gif"></img>
953 
954  FMOD_DSP_FFT_WINDOW_HANNING.
955  <img src = "hanning.gif"></img>
956 
957  FMOD_DSP_FFT_WINDOW_BLACKMAN.
958  <img src = "blackman.gif"></img>
959 
960  FMOD_DSP_FFT_WINDOW_BLACKMANHARRIS.
961  <img src = "blackmanharris.gif"></img>
962  </exclude>
963 
964  [PLATFORMS]
965  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
966 
967  [SEE_ALSO]
968  System::getSpectrum
969  Channel::getSpectrum
970  ]
971  */
972  public enum DSP_FFT_WINDOW :int
973  {
974  RECT, /* w[n] = 1.0 */
975  TRIANGLE, /* w[n] = TRI(2n/N) */
976  HAMMING, /* w[n] = 0.54 - (0.46 * COS(n/N) ) */
977  HANNING, /* w[n] = 0.5 * (1.0 - COS(n/N) ) */
978  BLACKMAN, /* w[n] = 0.42 - (0.5 * COS(n/N) ) + (0.08 * COS(2.0 * n/N) ) */
979  BLACKMANHARRIS, /* w[n] = 0.35875 - (0.48829 * COS(1.0 * n/N)) + (0.14128 * COS(2.0 * n/N)) - (0.01168 * COS(3.0 * n/N)) */
980 
981  MAX
982  }
983

985  /*
986  [ENUM]
987  [
988  [DESCRIPTION]
989  List of interpolation types that the FMOD Ex software mixer supports.
990 
991  [REMARKS]
992  The default resampler type is FMOD_DSP_RESAMPLER_LINEAR.<br>
993  Use System::setSoftwareFormat to tell FMOD the resampling quality you require for FMOD_SOFTWARE based sounds.
994 
995  [PLATFORMS]
996  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
997 
998  [SEE_ALSO]
999  System::setSoftwareFormat
1000  System::getSoftwareFormat
1001  ]
1002  */
1003  public enum DSP_RESAMPLER :int
1004  {
1005  NOINTERP, /* No interpolation. High frequency aliasing hiss will be audible depending on the sample rate of the sound. */
1006  LINEAR, /* Linear interpolation (default method). Fast and good quality, causes very slight lowpass effect on low frequency sounds. */
1007  CUBIC, /* Cubic interpolation. Slower than linear interpolation but better quality. */
1008  SPLINE, /* 5 point spline interpolation. Slowest resampling method but best quality. */
1009 
1010  MAX, /* Maximum number of resample methods supported. */
1011  }

1072  /*
1073  [ENUM]
1074  [
1075  [DESCRIPTION]
1076  Types of delay that can be used with Channel::setDelay / Channel::getDelay.
1077 
1078  [REMARKS]
1079  If you haven't called Channel::setDelay yet, if you call Channel::getDelay with FMOD_DELAYTYPE_DSPCLOCK_START it will return the
1080  equivalent global DSP clock value to determine when a channel started, so that you can use it for other channels to sync against.<br>
1081  <br>
1082  Use System::getDSPClock to also get the current dspclock time, a base for future calls to Channel::setDelay.<br>
1083  <br>
1084  Use FMOD_64BIT_ADD or FMOD_64BIT_SUB to add a hi/lo combination together and cope with wraparound.
1085  <br>
1086  If FMOD_DELAYTYPE_END_MS is specified, the value is not treated as a 64 bit number, just the delayhi value is used and it is treated as milliseconds.
1087 
1088  [PLATFORMS]
1089  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
1090 
1091  [SEE_ALSO]
1092  Channel::setDelay
1093  Channel::getDelay
1094  System::getDSPClock
1095  ]
1096  */
1097  public enum DELAYTYPE :int
1098  {
1099  END_MS, /* Delay at the end of the sound in milliseconds. Use delayhi only. Channel::isPlaying will remain true until this delay has passed even though the sound itself has stopped playing.*/
1100  DSPCLOCK_START, /* Time the sound started if Channel::getDelay is used, or if Channel::setDelay is used, the sound will delay playing until this exact tick. */
1101  DSPCLOCK_END, /* Time the sound should end. If this is non-zero, the channel will go silent at this exact tick. */
1102  DSPCLOCK_PAUSE, /* Time the sound should pause. If this is non-zero, the channel will pause at this exact tick. */
1103 
1104  MAX /* Maximum number of tag datatypes supported. */
1105  }
1106 
1107  public class DELAYTYPE_UTILITY
1108  {
1109  void FMOD_64BIT_ADD(ref uint hi1, ref uint lo1, uint hi2, uint lo2)
1110  {
1111  hi1 += (uint)((hi2) + ((((lo1) + (lo2)) < (lo1)) ? 1 : 0));
1112  lo1 += (lo2);
1113  }
1114 
1115  void FMOD_64BIT_SUB(ref uint hi1, ref uint lo1, uint hi2, uint lo2)
1116  {
1117  hi1 -= (uint)((hi2) + ((((lo1) - (lo2)) > (lo1)) ? 1 : 0));
1118  lo1 -= (lo2);
1119  }
1120  }

1186  /*
1187  [ENUM]
1188  [
1189  [DESCRIPTION]
1190  List of time types that can be returned by Sound::getLength and used with Channel::setPosition or Channel::getPosition.
1191 
1192  [REMARKS]
1193 
1194  [PLATFORMS]
1195  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
1196 
1197  [SEE_ALSO]
1198  Sound::getLength
1199  Channel::setPosition
1200  Channel::getPosition
1201  ]
1202  */
1203  public enum TIMEUNIT
1204  {
1205  MS = 0x00000001, /* Milliseconds. */
1206  PCM = 0x00000002, /* PCM Samples, related to milliseconds * samplerate / 1000. */
1207  PCMBYTES = 0x00000004, /* Bytes, related to PCM samples * channels * datawidth (ie 16bit = 2 bytes). */
1208  RAWBYTES = 0x00000008, /* Raw file bytes of (compressed) sound data (does not include headers). Only used by Sound::getLength and Channel::getPosition. */
1209  PCMFRACTION = 0x00000010, /* Fractions of 1 PCM sample. Unsigned int range 0 to 0xFFFFFFFF. Used for sub-sample granularity for DSP purposes. */
1210  MODORDER = 0x00000100, /* MOD/S3M/XM/IT. Order in a sequenced module format. Use Sound::getFormat to determine the format. */
1211  MODROW = 0x00000200, /* MOD/S3M/XM/IT. Current row in a sequenced module format. Sound::getLength will return the number if rows in the currently playing or seeked to pattern. */
1212  MODPATTERN = 0x00000400, /* MOD/S3M/XM/IT. Current pattern in a sequenced module format. Sound::getLength will return the number of patterns in the song and Channel::getPosition will return the currently playing pattern. */
1213  SENTENCE_MS = 0x00010000, /* Currently playing subsound in a sentence time in milliseconds. */
1214  SENTENCE_PCM = 0x00020000, /* Currently playing subsound in a sentence time in PCM Samples, related to milliseconds * samplerate / 1000. */
1215  SENTENCE_PCMBYTES = 0x00040000, /* Currently playing subsound in a sentence time in bytes, related to PCM samples * channels * datawidth (ie 16bit = 2 bytes). */
1216  SENTENCE = 0x00080000, /* Currently playing sentence index according to the channel. */
1217  SENTENCE_SUBSOUND = 0x00100000, /* Currently playing subsound index in a sentence. */
1218  BUFFERED = 0x10000000, /* Time value as seen by buffered stream. This is always ahead of audible time, and is only used for processing. */
1219  }

1222  /*
1223  [ENUM]
1224  [
1225  [DESCRIPTION]
1226  When creating a multichannel sound, FMOD will pan them to their default speaker locations, for example a 6 channel sound will default to one channel per 5.1 output speaker.<br>
1227  Another example is a stereo sound. It will default to left = front left, right = front right.<br>
1228  <br>
1229  This is for sounds that are not 'default'. For example you might have a sound that is 6 channels but actually made up of 3 stereo pairs, that should all be located in front left, front right only.
1230 
1231  [REMARKS]
1232  For full flexibility of speaker assignments, use Channel::setSpeakerLevels. This functionality is cheaper, uses less memory and easier to use.
1233 
1234  [PLATFORMS]
1235  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
1236 
1237  [SEE_ALSO]
1238  FMOD_CREATESOUNDEXINFO
1239  Channel::setSpeakerLevels
1240  ]
1241  */
1242  public enum SPEAKERMAPTYPE
1243  {
1244  DEFAULT, /* This is the default, and just means FMOD decides which speakers it puts the source channels. */
1245  ALLMONO, /* This means the sound is made up of all mono sounds. All voices will be panned to the front center by default in this case. */
1246  ALLSTEREO, /* This means the sound is made up of all stereo sounds. All voices will be panned to front left and front right alternating every second channel. */
1247  _51_PROTOOLS /* Map a 5.1 sound to use protools L C R Ls Rs LFE mapping. Will return an error if not a 6 channel sound. */
1248  }

1250 
1251  /*
1252  [STRUCTURE]
1253  [
1254  [DESCRIPTION]
1255  Use this structure with System::createSound when more control is needed over loading.
1256  The possible reasons to use this with System::createSound are:
1257  <li>Loading a file from memory.
1258  <li>Loading a file from within another larger (possibly wad/pak) file, by giving the loader an offset and length.
1259  <li>To create a user created / non file based sound.
1260  <li>To specify a starting subsound to seek to within a multi-sample sounds (ie FSB/DLS/SF2) when created as a stream.
1261  <li>To specify which subsounds to load for multi-sample sounds (ie FSB/DLS/SF2) so that memory is saved and only a subset is actually loaded/read from disk.
1262  <li>To specify 'piggyback' read and seek callbacks for capture of sound data as fmod reads and decodes it. Useful for ripping decoded PCM data from sounds as they are loaded / played.
1263  <li>To specify a MIDI DLS/SF2 sample set file to load when opening a MIDI file.
1264  See below on what members to fill for each of the above types of sound you want to create.
1265 
1266  [REMARKS]
1267  This structure is optional! Specify 0 or NULL in System::createSound if you don't need it!
1268 
1269  Members marked with [in] mean the user sets the value before passing it to the function.
1270  Members marked with [out] mean FMOD sets the value to be used after the function exits.
1271 
1272  <u>Loading a file from memory.</u>
1273  <li>Create the sound using the FMOD_OPENMEMORY flag.
1274  <li>Mandantory. Specify 'length' for the size of the memory block in bytes.
1275  <li>Other flags are optional.
1276 
1277 
1278  <u>Loading a file from within another larger (possibly wad/pak) file, by giving the loader an offset and length.</u>
1279  <li>Mandantory. Specify 'fileoffset' and 'length'.
1280  <li>Other flags are optional.
1281 
1282 
1283  <u>To create a user created / non file based sound.</u>
1284  <li>Create the sound using the FMOD_OPENUSER flag.
1285  <li>Mandantory. Specify 'defaultfrequency, 'numchannels' and 'format'.
1286  <li>Other flags are optional.
1287 
1288 
1289  <u>To specify a starting subsound to seek to and flush with, within a multi-sample stream (ie FSB/DLS/SF2).</u>
1290 
1291  <li>Mandantory. Specify 'initialsubsound'.
1292 
1293 
1294  <u>To specify which subsounds to load for multi-sample sounds (ie FSB/DLS/SF2) so that memory is saved and only a subset is actually loaded/read from disk.</u>
1295 
1296  <li>Mandantory. Specify 'inclusionlist' and 'inclusionlistnum'.
1297 
1298 
1299  <u>To specify 'piggyback' read and seek callbacks for capture of sound data as fmod reads and decodes it. Useful for ripping decoded PCM data from sounds as they are loaded / played.</u>
1300 
1301  <li>Mandantory. Specify 'pcmreadcallback' and 'pcmseekcallback'.
1302 
1303 
1304  <u>To specify a MIDI DLS/SF2 sample set file to load when opening a MIDI file.</u>
1305 
1306  <li>Mandantory. Specify 'dlsname'.
1307 
1308 
1309  Setting the 'decodebuffersize' is for cpu intensive codecs that may be causing stuttering, not file intensive codecs (ie those from CD or netstreams) which are normally altered with System::setStreamBufferSize. As an example of cpu intensive codecs, an mp3 file will take more cpu to decode than a PCM wav file.
1310  If you have a stuttering effect, then it is using more cpu than the decode buffer playback rate can keep up with. Increasing the decode buffersize will most likely solve this problem.
1311 
1312  [PLATFORMS]
1313  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
1314 
1315  [SEE_ALSO]
1316  System::createSound
1317  System::setStreamBufferSize
1318  FMOD_MODE
1319  ]
1320  */
1321  [StructLayout(LayoutKind.Sequential)]
1322  public struct CREATESOUNDEXINFO
1323  {
1324  public int cbsize; /* [in] Size of this structure. This is used so the structure can be expanded in the future and still work on older versions of FMOD Ex. */
1325  public uint length; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Size in bytes of file to load, or sound to create (in this case only if FMOD_OPENUSER is used). Required if loading from memory. If 0 is specified, then it will use the size of the file (unless loading from memory then an error will be returned). */
1326  public uint fileoffset; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Offset from start of the file to start loading from. This is useful for loading files from inside big data files. */
1327  public int numchannels; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Number of channels in a sound specified only if OPENUSER is used. */
1328  public int defaultfrequency; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Default frequency of sound in a sound specified only if OPENUSER is used. Other formats use the frequency determined by the file format. */
1329  public SOUND_FORMAT format; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 or SOUND_FORMAT_NONE to ignore. Format of the sound specified only if OPENUSER is used. Other formats use the format determined by the file format. */
1330  public uint decodebuffersize; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. For streams. This determines the size of the double buffer (in PCM samples) that a stream uses. Use this for user created streams if you want to determine the size of the callback buffer passed to you. Specify 0 to use FMOD's default size which is currently equivalent to 400ms of the sound format created/loaded. */
1331  public int initialsubsound; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. In a multi-sample file format such as .FSB/.DLS/.SF2, specify the initial subsound to seek to, only if CREATESTREAM is used. */
1332  public int numsubsounds; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore or have no subsounds. In a user created multi-sample sound, specify the number of subsounds within the sound that are accessable with Sound::getSubSound / SoundGetSubSound. */
1333  public IntPtr inclusionlist; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. In a multi-sample format such as .FSB/.DLS/.SF2 it may be desirable to specify only a subset of sounds to be loaded out of the whole file. This is an array of subsound indicies to load into memory when created. */
1334  public int inclusionlistnum; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. This is the number of integers contained within the */
1335  public SOUND_PCMREADCALLBACK pcmreadcallback; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Callback to 'piggyback' on FMOD's read functions and accept or even write PCM data while FMOD is opening the sound. Used for user sounds created with OPENUSER or for capturing decoded data as FMOD reads it. */
1336  public SOUND_PCMSETPOSCALLBACK pcmsetposcallback; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Callback for when the user calls a seeking function such as Channel::setPosition within a multi-sample sound, and for when it is opened.*/
1337  public SOUND_NONBLOCKCALLBACK nonblockcallback; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Callback for successful completion, or error while loading a sound that used the FMOD_NONBLOCKING flag.*/
1338  public string dlsname; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Filename for a DLS or SF2 sample set when loading a MIDI file. If not specified, on windows it will attempt to open /windows/system32/drivers/gm.dls, otherwise the MIDI will fail to open. */
1339  public string encryptionkey; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Key for encrypted FSB file. Without this key an encrypted FSB file will not load. */
1340  public int maxpolyphony; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ingore. For sequenced formats with dynamic channel allocation such as .MID and .IT, this specifies the maximum voice count allowed while playing. .IT defaults to 64. .MID defaults to 32. */
1341  public IntPtr userdata; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. This is user data to be attached to the sound during creation. Access via Sound::getUserData. */
1342  public SOUND_TYPE suggestedsoundtype; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 or FMOD_SOUND_TYPE_UNKNOWN to ignore. Instead of scanning all codec types, use this to speed up loading by making it jump straight to this codec. */
1343  public FILE_OPENCALLBACK useropen; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Callback for opening this file. */
1344  public FILE_CLOSECALLBACK userclose; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Callback for closing this file. */
1345  public FILE_READCALLBACK userread; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Callback for reading from this file. */
1346  public FILE_SEEKCALLBACK userseek; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Callback for seeking within this file. */
1347  public FILE_ASYNCREADCALLBACK userasyncread; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Callback for asyncronously reading from this file. */
1348  public FILE_ASYNCCANCELCALLBACK userasynccancel; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Callback for cancelling an asyncronous read. */
1349  public SPEAKERMAPTYPE speakermap; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Use this to differ the way fmod maps multichannel sounds to speakers. See FMOD_SPEAKERMAPTYPE for more. */
1350  public IntPtr initialsoundgroup; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Specify a sound group if required, to put sound in as it is created. */
1351  public uint initialseekposition; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. For streams. Specify an initial position to seek the stream to. */
1352  public TIMEUNIT initialseekpostype; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. For streams. Specify the time unit for the position set in initialseekposition. */
1353  public int ignoresetfilesystem; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Set to 1 to use fmod's built in file system. Ignores setFileSystem callbacks and also FMOD_CREATESOUNEXINFO file callbacks. Useful for specific cases where you don't want to use your own file system but want to use fmod's file system (ie net streaming). */
1354  public int cddaforceaspi; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. For CDDA sounds only - if non-zero use ASPI instead of NTSCSI to access the specified CD/DVD device. */
1355  public uint audioqueuepolicy; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 or FMOD_AUDIOQUEUE_CODECPOLICY_DEFAULT to ignore. Policy used to determine whether hardware or software is used for decoding, see FMOD_AUDIOQUEUE_CODECPOLICY for options (iOS >= 3.0 required, otherwise only hardware is available) */
1356  public uint minmidigranularity; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Allows you to set a minimum desired MIDI mixer granularity. Values smaller than 512 give greater than default accuracy at the cost of more CPU and vise versa. Specify 0 for default (512 samples). */
1357  public int nonblockthreadid; /* [in] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Specifies a thread index to execute non blocking load on. Allows for up to 5 threads to be used for loading at once. This is to avoid one load blocking another. Maximum value = 4. */
1358  }

1361  /*
1362  [STRUCTURE]
1363  [
1364  [DESCRIPTION]
1365  Structure defining a reverb environment.<br>
1366  <br>
1367  For more indepth descriptions of the reverb properties under win32, please see the EAX2 and EAX3
1368  documentation at http://developer.creative.com/ under the 'downloads' section.<br>
1369  If they do not have the EAX3 documentation, then most information can be attained from
1370  the EAX2 documentation, as EAX3 only adds some more parameters and functionality on top of
1371  EAX2.
1372 
1373  [REMARKS]
1374  Note the default reverb properties are the same as the FMOD_PRESET_GENERIC preset.<br>
1375  Note that integer values that typically range from -10,000 to 1000 are represented in
1376  decibels, and are of a logarithmic scale, not linear, wheras float values are always linear.<br>
1377  <br>
1378  The numerical values listed below are the maximum, minimum and default values for each variable respectively.<br>
1379  <br>
1380  <b>SUPPORTED</b> next to each parameter means the platform the parameter can be set on. Some platforms support all parameters and some don't.<br>
1381  EAX means hardware reverb on FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_DSOUND on windows only (must use FMOD_HARDWARE), on soundcards that support EAX 1 to 4.<br>
1382  EAX4 means hardware reverb on FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_DSOUND on windows only (must use FMOD_HARDWARE), on soundcards that support EAX 4.<br>
1383  I3DL2 means hardware reverb on FMOD_OUTPUTTYPE_DSOUND on windows only (must use FMOD_HARDWARE), on soundcards that support I3DL2 non EAX native reverb.<br>
1384  GC means Nintendo Gamecube hardware reverb (must use FMOD_HARDWARE).<br>
1385  WII means Nintendo Wii hardware reverb (must use FMOD_HARDWARE).<br>
1386  PS2 means Playstation 2 hardware reverb (must use FMOD_HARDWARE).<br>
1387  SFX means FMOD SFX software reverb. This works on any platform that uses FMOD_SOFTWARE for loading sounds.<br>
1388  <br>
1389  Members marked with [in] mean the user sets the value before passing it to the function.<br>
1390  Members marked with [out] mean FMOD sets the value to be used after the function exits.<br>
1391 
1392  [PLATFORMS]
1393  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
1394 
1395  [SEE_ALSO]
1396  System::setReverbProperties
1397  System::getReverbProperties
1398  FMOD_REVERB_PRESETS
1399  FMOD_REVERB_FLAGS
1400  ]
1401  */
1402  [StructLayout(LayoutKind.Sequential)]
1403  public struct REVERB_PROPERTIES
1404  { /* MIN MAX DEFAULT DESCRIPTION */
1405  public int Instance; /* [in] 0 , 3 , 0 , EAX4 only. Environment Instance. 3 seperate reverbs simultaneously are possible. This specifies which one to set. (win32 only) */
1406  public int Environment; /* [in/out] -1 , 25 , -1 , sets all listener properties (win32/ps2) */
1407  public float EnvDiffusion; /* [in/out] 0.0 , 1.0 , 1.0 , environment diffusion (win32/xbox) */
1408  public int Room; /* [in/out] -10000, 0 , -1000 , room effect level (at mid frequencies) (win32/xbox) */
1409  public int RoomHF; /* [in/out] -10000, 0 , -100 , relative room effect level at high frequencies (win32/xbox) */
1410  public int RoomLF; /* [in/out] -10000, 0 , 0 , relative room effect level at low frequencies (win32 only) */
1411  public float DecayTime; /* [in/out] 0.1 , 20.0 , 1.49 , reverberation decay time at mid frequencies (win32/xbox) */
1412  public float DecayHFRatio; /* [in/out] 0.1 , 2.0 , 0.83 , high-frequency to mid-frequency decay time ratio (win32/xbox) */
1413  public float DecayLFRatio; /* [in/out] 0.1 , 2.0 , 1.0 , low-frequency to mid-frequency decay time ratio (win32 only) */
1414  public int Reflections; /* [in/out] -10000, 1000 , -2602 , early reflections level relative to room effect (win32/xbox) */
1415  public float ReflectionsDelay; /* [in/out] 0.0 , 0.3 , 0.007 , initial reflection delay time (win32/xbox) */
1416  public int Reverb; /* [in/out] -10000, 2000 , 200 , late reverberation level relative to room effect (win32/xbox) */
1417  public float ReverbDelay; /* [in/out] 0.0 , 0.1 , 0.011 , late reverberation delay time relative to initial reflection (win32/xbox) */
1418  public float ModulationTime; /* [in/out] 0.04 , 4.0 , 0.25 , modulation time (win32 only) */
1419  public float ModulationDepth; /* [in/out] 0.0 , 1.0 , 0.0 , modulation depth (win32 only) */
1420  public float HFReference; /* [in/out] 1000.0, 20000 , 5000.0 , reference high frequency (hz) (win32/xbox) */
1421  public float LFReference; /* [in/out] 20.0 , 1000.0, 250.0 , reference low frequency (hz) (win32 only) */
1422  public float Diffusion; /* [in/out] 0.0 , 100.0 , 100.0 , Value that controls the echo density in the late reverberation decay. (xbox only) */
1423  public float Density; /* [in/out] 0.0 , 100.0 , 100.0 , Value that controls the modal density in the late reverberation decay (xbox only) */
1424  public uint Flags; /* [in/out] REVERB_FLAGS - modifies the behavior of above properties (win32/ps2) */
1425 
1426  #region wrapperinternal
1427  public REVERB_PROPERTIES(int instance, int environment, float envDiffusion, int room, int roomHF, int roomLF,
1428  float decayTime, float decayHFRatio, float decayLFRatio, int reflections, float reflectionsDelay,
1429  int reverb, float reverbDelay, float modulationTime, float modulationDepth, float hfReference,
1430  float lfReference, float diffusion, float density, uint flags)
1431  {
1432  Instance = instance;
1433  Environment = environment;
1434  EnvDiffusion = envDiffusion;
1435  Room = room;
1436  RoomHF = roomHF;
1437  RoomLF = roomLF;
1438  DecayTime = decayTime;
1439  DecayHFRatio = decayHFRatio;
1440  DecayLFRatio = decayLFRatio;
1441  Reflections = reflections;
1442  ReflectionsDelay = reflectionsDelay;
1443  Reverb = reverb;
1444  ReverbDelay = reverbDelay;
1445  ModulationTime = modulationTime;
1446  ModulationDepth = modulationDepth;
1447  HFReference = hfReference;
1448  LFReference = lfReference;
1449  Diffusion = diffusion;
1450  Density = density;
1451  Flags = flags;
1452  }
1453  #endregion
1454  }

1530  /*
1531  [STRUCTURE]
1532  [
1533  [DESCRIPTION]
1534  Structure defining the properties for a reverb source, related to a FMOD channel.
1535 
1536  For more indepth descriptions of the reverb properties under win32, please see the EAX3
1537  documentation at http://developer.creative.com/ under the 'downloads' section.
1538  If they do not have the EAX3 documentation, then most information can be attained from
1539  the EAX2 documentation, as EAX3 only adds some more parameters and functionality on top of
1540  EAX2.
1541 
1542  Note the default reverb properties are the same as the PRESET_GENERIC preset.
1543  Note that integer values that typically range from -10,000 to 1000 are represented in
1544  decibels, and are of a logarithmic scale, not linear, wheras FLOAT values are typically linear.
1545  PORTABILITY: Each member has the platform it supports in braces ie (win32/xbox).
1546  Some reverb parameters are only supported in win32 and some only on xbox. If all parameters are set then
1547  the reverb should product a similar effect on either platform.
1548  Linux and FMODCE do not support the reverb api.
1549 
1550  The numerical values listed below are the maximum, minimum and default values for each variable respectively.
1551 
1552  [REMARKS]
1553  For EAX4 support with multiple reverb environments, set FMOD_REVERB_CHANNELFLAGS_ENVIRONMENT0,
1554  FMOD_REVERB_CHANNELFLAGS_ENVIRONMENT1 or/and FMOD_REVERB_CHANNELFLAGS_ENVIRONMENT2 in the flags member
1555  of FMOD_REVERB_CHANNELPROPERTIES to specify which environment instance(s) to target.
1556  Only up to 2 environments to target can be specified at once. Specifying three will result in an error.
1557  If the sound card does not support EAX4, the environment flag is ignored.
1558 
1559  [PLATFORMS]
1560  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3, Wii
1561 
1562  [SEE_ALSO]
1563  Channel::setReverbProperties
1564  Channel::getReverbProperties
1565  REVERB_CHANNELFLAGS
1566  ]
1567  */
1568  [StructLayout(LayoutKind.Sequential)]
1569  public struct REVERB_CHANNELPROPERTIES
1570  { /* MIN MAX DEFAULT DESCRIPTION */
1571  public int Direct; /* [in/out] -10000, 1000, 0, direct path level (at low and mid frequencies) (win32/xbox) */
1572  public int Room; /* [in/out] -10000, 1000, 0, room effect level (at low and mid frequencies) (win32/xbox) */
1573  public uint Flags; /* [in/out] REVERB_CHANNELFLAGS - modifies the behavior of properties (win32) */
1574  public IntPtr ConnectionPoint; /* [in/out] See remarks. DSP network location to connect reverb for this channel. (SUPPORTED:SFX only).*/
1575  }

1605  /*
1606  [STRUCTURE]
1607  [
1608  [DESCRIPTION]
1609  Settings for advanced features like configuring memory and cpu usage for the FMOD_CREATECOMPRESSEDSAMPLE feature.
1610 
1611  [REMARKS]
1612  maxMPEGcodecs / maxADPCMcodecs / maxXMAcodecs will determine the maximum cpu usage of playing realtime samples. Use this to lower potential excess cpu usage and also control memory usage.<br>
1613 
1614  [PLATFORMS]
1615  Win32, Win64, Linux, Linux64, Macintosh, Xbox360, PlayStation Portable, PlayStation 3
1616 
1617  [SEE_ALSO]
1618  System::setAdvancedSettings
1619  System::getAdvancedSettings
1620  ]
1621  */
1622  [StructLayout(LayoutKind.Sequential)]
1623  public struct ADVANCEDSETTINGS
1624  {
1625  public int cbsize; /* Size of structure. Use sizeof(FMOD_ADVANCEDSETTINGS) */
1626  public int maxMPEGcodecs; /* For use with FMOD_CREATECOMPRESSEDSAMPLE only. Mpeg codecs consume 48,696 per instance and this number will determine how many mpeg channels can be played simultaneously. Default = 16. */
1627  public int maxADPCMcodecs; /* For use with FMOD_CREATECOMPRESSEDSAMPLE only. ADPCM codecs consume 1k per instance and this number will determine how many ADPCM channels can be played simultaneously. Default = 32. */
1628  public int maxXMAcodecs; /* For use with FMOD_CREATECOMPRESSEDSAMPLE only. XMA codecs consume 8k per instance and this number will determine how many XMA channels can be played simultaneously. Default = 32. */
1629  public int maxPCMcodecs; /* [in/out] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. For use with PS3 only. PCM codecs consume 12,672 bytes per instance and this number will determine how many streams and PCM voices can be played simultaneously. Default = 16 */
1630  public int maxCELTcodecs; /* [in/out] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. For use with FMOD_CREATECOMPRESSEDSAMPLE only. CELT codecs consume 11,500 bytes per instance and this number will determine how many CELT channels can be played simultaneously. Default = 16 */
1631  public int ASIONumChannels; /* [in/out] */
1632  public IntPtr ASIOChannelList; /* [in/out] */
1633  public IntPtr ASIOSpeakerList; /* [in/out] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Pointer to a list of speakers that the ASIO channels map to. This can be called after System::init to remap ASIO output. */
1634  public int max3DReverbDSPs; /* [in/out] The max number of 3d reverb DSP's in the system. */
1635  public float HRTFMinAngle; /* [in/out] For use with FMOD_INIT_HRTF_LOWPASS. The angle (0-360) of a 3D sound from the listener's forward vector at which the HRTF function begins to have an effect. Default = 180.0. */
1636  public float HRTFMaxAngle; /* [in/out] For use with FMOD_INIT_HRTF_LOWPASS. The angle (0-360) of a 3D sound from the listener's forward vector at which the HRTF function begins to have maximum effect. Default = 360.0. */
1637  public float HRTFFreq; /* [in/out] For use with FMOD_INIT_HRTF_LOWPASS. The cutoff frequency of the HRTF's lowpass filter function when at maximum effect. (i.e. at HRTFMaxAngle). Default = 4000.0. */
1638  public float vol0virtualvol; /* [in/out] For use with FMOD_INIT_VOL0_BECOMES_VIRTUAL. If this flag is used, and the volume is 0.0, then the sound will become virtual. Use this value to raise the threshold to a different point where a sound goes virtual. */
1639  public int eventqueuesize; /* [in/out] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. For use with FMOD Event system only. Specifies the number of slots available for simultaneous non blocking loads. Default = 32. */
1640  public uint defaultDecodeBufferSize; /* [in/out] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. For streams. This determines the default size of the double buffer (in milliseconds) that a stream uses. Default = 400ms */
1641  public IntPtr debugLogFilename; /* [in/out] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. Gives fmod's logging system a path/filename. Normally the log is placed in the same directory as the executable and called fmod.log. When using System::getAdvancedSettings, provide at least 256 bytes of memory to copy into. */
1642  public ushort profileport; /* [in/out] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. For use with FMOD_INIT_ENABLE_PROFILE. Specify the port to listen on for connections by the profiler application. */
1643  public uint geometryMaxFadeTime; /* [in/out] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. The maximum time in miliseconds it takes for a channel to fade to the new level when its occlusion changes. */
1644  public uint maxSpectrumWaveDataBuffers; /* [in/out] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. The maximum number of buffers for use with getWaveData/getSpectrum. */
1645  public uint musicSystemCacheDelay; /* [in/out] Optional. Specify 0 to ignore. The delay the music system should allow for loading a sample from disk (in milliseconds). Default = 400 ms. */
1646  }

1673 
1674  /*
1675  FMOD System factory functions. Use this to create an FMOD System Instance. below you will see System_Init/Close to get started.
1676  */
1677  public class Factory
1678  {
1679  public static RESULT System_Create(ref System system)
1680  {
1681 #if WIN64
1682  if (IntPtr.Size != 8)
1683  {
1684  /* Attempting to use 64-bit FMOD dll with 32-bit application.*/
1685 
1686  return RESULT.ERR_FILE_BAD;
1687  }
1688 #else
1689  if (IntPtr.Size != 4)
1690  {
1691  /* Attempting to use 32-bit FMOD dll with 64-bit application. A likely cause of this error
1692  * is targetting platform 'Any CPU'. You cannot link to unmanaged dll with 'Any CPU'
1693  * target.
1694  *
1695  * For 32-bit applications: set the platform to 'x86'.
1696  *
1697  * For 64-bit applications:
1698  * 1. set the platform to x64
1699  * 2. add the conditional complication symbol WIN64
1700  * 3. download the win64 fmod release
1701  * 4. copy the fmodex64.dll to the location of the .exe file for your application */
1702 
1703  return RESULT.ERR_FILE_BAD;
1704  }
1705 #endif
1706 
1707  RESULT result = RESULT.OK;
1708  IntPtr systemraw = new IntPtr();
1709  System systemnew = null;
1710 
1711  result = FMOD_System_Create(ref systemraw);
1712  if (result != RESULT.OK)
1713  {
1714  return result;
1715  }
1716 
1717  systemnew = new System();
1718  systemnew.setRaw(systemraw);
1719  system = systemnew;
1720 
1721  return result;
1722  }
1723 
1724 
1725  #region importfunctions
1726 
1727  [DllImport (VERSION.dll)]
1728  private static extern RESULT FMOD_System_Create (ref IntPtr system);
1729 
1730  #endregion
1731  }

2024  {

2026  }
2027  catch

2032  {
2033  return result;

2037  {
2038  soundnew = new Sound();
2039  soundnew.setRaw(soundraw);
2040  sound = soundnew;
2041  }
2042  else
2043  {
2044  sound.setRaw(soundraw);
2045  }
2046 
2047  return result;

3054  public RESULT getSystemObject (ref System system)
3055  {
3056  RESULT result = RESULT.OK;
3057  IntPtr systemraw = new IntPtr();
3058  System systemnew = null;
3059 
3060  try
3061  {
3062  result = FMOD_Sound_GetSystemObject(soundraw, ref systemraw);
3063  }
3064  catch
3065  {
3066  result = RESULT.ERR_INVALID_PARAM;
3067  }
3068  if (result != RESULT.OK)
3069  {
3070  return result;
3071  }
3072 
3073  if (system == null)
3074  {
3075  systemnew = new System();
3076  systemnew.setRaw(systemraw);
3077  system = systemnew;
3078  }
3079  else
3080  {
3081  system.setRaw(systemraw);
3082  }
3083  return result;
3084  }
